      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>asm495</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> What I suspect happens is that any PC or NPC can have any number of effects on it (whether buffs or DoTs etc) but it does NOT keep track of who put that effect on them.  This means that only one of any particular effect can be on them.  They probably also have a database table which details how effects stack or overwrite others.</P><P>This is sensible for buffs as Verant don't want PCs wandering around with 2 Aego's on them.  However, what this means is that a mob can only have one DoT cast on them as it can only have the effect once as the engine has no comprehension of where the first one came from.</P><P>What would need to happen for DoT stacking is for all effects to be tagged with who cast it.  This means that all effects would have to carry this additional overhead and place quite a bit of extra load on the server (just think of the number of buffs, DoTs etc. people use).</P><P>So whilst it may seem simple it could have quite serious knock-on effects and would also require some major modification to a very mature piece of code for handling effects.</P><P>This is all in theory as I have no idea how they actually do it and is just based off what I would think is the most logical way of doing it.</P><P><BR><A HREF="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=16832" TARGET="_NEW">Draknn Fels, Warlock</A><BR>Divide et Impera, Bristlebane</font></td>
      </tr>
