      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Kuotat</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> DOT stacking would seem to be easy enough to fix, to us, but we're also not privy to the code involved.  EQ has been released for 3 years and was in development for 2 years prior to that.  I've worked in a similar situation and trust me, the code under the hood is probably looking DAMN scary.  Not to mention, the programmer/s that have worked on it have probably left or moved on.  Basically, 3-5 programmers have had their hands on the code and it's held together with duct tape - bailing wire and no one really has a good handle on what's going on.  </P><P>From what I've seen is that it appears that spells override each other.  Seems there is a spell "order".  Splurt will land, but not if Cessation of Cor has already been cast.  CoC has a "higher" order then Splurt.  Generally the higher level of spell line X will override and not allow lower spells of the same line to be cast on a MOB once it's been landed.  It also appears that there is a Level order as well.  If a 50 level necro casts BOD on a MOB and then a 51 casts, they can both land the spell (note BOD damage to the MOB is only considered once and just gets refreshed when the second one lands) and both get the right amount of healing.  If the 51 casts first the level 50 won't get his BOD to land (this USED to be a bug, it might have been fixed).  </P><P>I do not envy the programmer that gets to throw away his weekend for the DOT mess, but I do think that it's high time this issue was at least addressed either by a fix or some VI person talking about it.</P><P></P><P><A target=B href="http://www.magelo.com/eq_view_profile.html?num=95266" ><img src="http://www.isomedia.com/homes/kuoman/Kuotat.jpg" border=0></a></font></td>
      </tr>
      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Wurtin</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> The message for when the spell wears off doesn't have to be coded on the MOB side of the equation either.  They may keep that portion on the Casting character side in order to save bandwidth.  Regardless, the point is the code involved in this isn't trivial, and as stated before, after 5 years of massaging and tweaking and poor design up front, you could very well have a major mess to try to change it.  That's why design of any system is so important, because if it's not done well, you can get yourself into a corner that is very painful ($$$) and risky to get out of.  By risk I mean introducing changes to the base game engine that will have major ramifications not just on necros, but on every other dot casting PC and NPC.</P><P>To answer your question, Dot stacking woulndn't be that difficult to code if we were starting from a clean slate.  But they don't have anywhere near a clean slate to work from.</P><P>Wurtin<BR>58th lvl Defiler of E'ci</P><P>“All that is necessary for the triumph of evil is for good men to do nothing.” Edmund Burke</font></td>
