      <TR>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'
 nowrap><b><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'>Hartsman</font></b></td>
        <TD bgcolor='dimgray' valign='top'><font color='white' face='Verdana, Arial, Helvetica' size='2'> DoT stacking has been mentioned enough times in the past (both distant and recent) as something we'd consider doing that I'd like to break character and explain in a bit of detail why it's harder than anyone had assumed.</P><P>(Please bear in mind - I'm still mostly the new guy.  I've played forever, but I haven't been on this side of this particular discussion yet. :)</P><P><BR>UsulDaNeriak wrote:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>as i know BoD doesnt stack. both necs get healed, but one everwrites the others dmg. general opinion i have read so far was, BoD dmg doesnt stack. however, maybe i am wrong.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>You are certainly not wrong.  Quite the contrary - You couldn't be more correct. </P><P>Zarloth wrote:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>I suspect the stacking code is a huge mess. It was made with only a few limited spell lines in mind, and now with all new spells and stuff, the limit is hit.<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>The observation that "It was made with only a few limited spell lines in mind..." is 100%, dead-on correct, with all of the associated difficulties that you might assume.</P><P>Please assume for a moment that some of those difficulties include, for example, an extremely limited amount of storage for each effect (buff/debuff), for each spell, for each PC, for each NPC, and so on.</P><P>And further, that those extents were excruciatingly painful to change.  </P><P><BR>Sskeli wrote:<BR><BLOCKQUOTE id=quote><font size=1 face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" id=quote>quote:<hr height=1 noshade id=quote>Yes the "who" of the casting is kept track of...how do you think you get the 'your spell has worn off' message?<hr height=1 noshade id=quote></BLOCKQUOTE id=quote></font id=quote><font face="Verdana, Arial, Helvetica" size=2 id=quote></P><P>...which is an absolutely logical assumption, and the vast majority of the time, it's correct.<BR> </P><P>Unfortunately, there's one problem, and that's the problem that prevents us from just saying, "Yep! We can make this happen.  Give me 3 days..."</P><P>What happens to the "Wears off" message when you log/zone out, then log/zone back in?</P><P>99% of the time, you don't get it.</P><P>Unfortunately, the caster's identity is a best-guess.  </P><P><BR>...and therein lies the problem.  If we stacked DoTs using the same logic, every DoT in the game would become a zone-in/zone-out exploitfest.  </P><P>Not that the majority of people would do such a thing.  We can probably all agree, though, that writing to the majority in this case means that the minority will take undue advantage.</P><P><BR>That said, there are other changes that we're making that will make this type of change easier.  It just takes time to decode what's gone on over the years and make sure the bases are covered.</P><P><BR>A cleaner, shinier EverQuest will be able to bring this back into the realm of the possible.  In the meanwhile, the best that I can offer are my apologies if this is something that was promised that we haven't delivered on.</P><P>Hope that helps at least a little. :)</P><P>- Scott</P><P><BR>(Edited to clip out some extraneous editorializing. :)</P><P>Edited by - Hartsman on 03/26/2002  00:37:34</font></td>
